explanation:
For MISRA dead-code analysis you must know (1) which branches are actually compiled and (2) whether calls inside the function are reachable and/or have side effects so that their removal would change program behaviour. Concrete needs:

- mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_: needed to determine possible return values and side effects of the first/alternative affinity-based probe; if it can return >0 or has observable side effects then subsequent calls are not dead.
- mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_cpuset_getaffinity_: same reason for the cpuset-based probe — its return behaviour and side effects decide whether later calls are necessary.
- mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_sched_getaffinity_np_: same — provides the non-portable fallback probe; required to know if this step is effective or has side effects.
- mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count_w32_: Windows-specific probe — required to know whether it produces results or side effects on some builds.

- __linux__ and __GLIBC__: these preprocessor macros determine which call ordering/blocks are compiled. To decide if code is dead you must know the active compilation configuration; code excluded by #if is not subject to this rule in the compiled build.

- detect_cpu_core_count, detect_process_cpu_core_count, mhd_tool_get_system_cpu_count: these callers are required to establish reachability of mhd_tool_get_proc_cpu_count in the whole project (i.e. whether the function itself is ever invoked). If the target function is never called (transitive reachability), it is dead; if it is called but callers only invoke it in contexts where its internal operations are redundant, that must be shown by inspecting these callers as well.

Provide the implementations/prototypes and any global state these symbols read/modify so the next agent can judge whether removing any call/operation would alter program behaviour.
